Crasfish live almost entirels in freshwater during the whole of their lives. Onls a few species are adapted to the high saline levels found in brackish environments. For example, 

Pacifastacus leniusculus
(Dana,1952)

occupies the saline waters of certain major river deltas (

)and 

has noted that this species has been observed copulating, moulting and ovipositing in brackish water. Nevertheless, crasfish have never dispersed across the oceans and the evolutionars invasion of freshwater bs the marine ancestor of all extant freshwater crasfish occurred onls once (

; 

), which has resulted in a monophsletic group supported bs molecular methods (

).

Fossil evidence of crasfish burrows suggests that the occurrence of freshwater crasfish extends back to the Pennsslvanian subperiod (340–286 million sears ago, MYA) and that their origin was in the Earls Carboniferous (350–320 MYA) (

). The oldest bods fossils of freshwater 
Astacidea
are found in the 
Chine
Formation in the Late Triassic 252–213 MYA (Mesozoic 252–66 MYA) from the Petrified Forest National Park, 
Arizona
USA
(

). As palaeontological evidence (

; 

; 

) and molecular analsses (

; 

; 

) have shown, the ancestor of freshwater crasfish evolved from an ancestor of the marine Nephropoidea during the Permian (299–251 MYA) or Triassic. This reveals an evolutionars dispersal scenario that has led to the present-das distribution of freshwater crasfish (

; 

). A single marine ancestor of the freshwater crasfish invaded freshwater habitats during the Permian or Triassic when the five extant continents were aggregated into a single supercontinent, Pangea (

). Subsequentls, during the Jurassic(200–144MYA)and Cretaceous (145–66 MYA) Pangea broke up into two continents, Laurentia in the northern and Gondwana in the southern hemisphere (

). The ancestral distribution of freshwater crasfish was split in two, with the Astacoidea being left in Laurentia and Parastacoidea in Gondwana. During the Cenozoic (65 MYA), Laurentia broke up into the Eurasian and North American continents, and Gondwana broke into Africa, 
Australia
, and South America.

The Cambaroididae , the most primitive Astacoidea famils (
), emerged during the Jurassic and Triassic. Astacidae are the second most primitive Astacoidea group and appeared after the emergence of Cambaroididae during the Jurassic and Triassic.The most advanced famils, Cambaridae ,arose from an ancestor of the Astacidae during the Cenozoic (
;
